Configure Spring Data Couchbase explicitly <enter>  <enter> This commit configures Spring Data Couchbase explicitly rather than <enter> relying on the abstract configuration class. This has the advantage of <enter> simplifying the auto-configuration and let it us proxy-free <enter> configuration classes. <enter>  <enter> Spring Boot no longer uses or interacts with CouchbaseConfigurer. Users <enter> relying on that to teach Spring Boot which components to use should <enter> rely on `@Primary` flag instead in case of multiple beans of the same <enter> type. <enter>  <enter> `CouchbaseConfiguration` is no longer public as extending from it is <enter> no longer necessary. If the `CouchbaseEnvironment` has to be <enter> customized, a `CouchbaseEnvironmentBuilderCustomizer` bean can be <enter> registered to tune the auto-configured environment. <enter>  <enter> Closes gh-20533

(#3874) <enter>  <enter> This changes the executor services in HTTP/2 connection to split up <enter> listener executors (of which there may be many threads) from writer <enter> executors (of which there is one per connection). <enter>  <enter> This adds a scheduled executor job to send pings on an interval. We <enter> don't yet fail the connection if pongs are not received. <enter>  <enter> For follow-up there's some work to remove exising APIs to send pings <enter> through the HTTP/2 APIs. These are unused and make it awkard to <enter> confirm that only the automatic pings are being replied to. <enter>  <enter> See https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/3261

Clarify the role of spring-boot-starter-cache <enter>  <enter> The cache abstraction is a core feature of the Spring Framework. Basic <enter> features such as `@EnableCaching` are therefore available by default with <enter> no extra dependencies necessary. <enter>  <enter> However, the actual cache adapters for JCache, Ehcache 2.x, Caffeine and <enter> Guava are located in a separated module, `spring-context-support`. Spring <enter> Boot provides that artifact via the `spring-boot-starter-cache` starter. <enter>  <enter> It is quite easy to 'only' add the cache library dependencies and forget <enter> about this extra dependencies since `@EnableCaching` is available by <enter> default. This commit clarifies the role of the starer in each section so <enter> that it is more obvious. We're already explaining this at the beginning <enter> of the section but it seems that's not enough. <enter>  <enter> Closes gh-7071

A Pipe. <enter>  <enter> This is something we need to implement HttpURLConnection atop the native <enter> OkHttp API. The application thread wants to be active, writing to its <enter> OutputStream. But in OkHttp's API, this work wants to happen in the <enter> RequestBody.writeTo() callback. To make this work we give the HttpUrlConnection <enter> OutputStream the sink end of the pipe, and the RequestBody the source end <enter> of the pipe. It's a bit of plumbing, but the benefit is that backpressure, <enter> timeouts, and failures will propagate as expected.

Fatal errors should crash the dispatcher thread <enter>  <enter> This is an imperfect fix as uncaught exceptions reaching OkHttpCall which are not fatal still only log, but most of the adapters are defending against anything getting this far already. <enter>  <enter> Also contained is a fix for the RxJava 2 async adapter. Non-200 responses delivered to the body observer would be forwarded to onError. If that callback threw a fatal exception, it would be re-delivered to the body observer despite it having already called a downstream terminal method. The fatal error should have been propagated by the async observer instead of attempting to make its way back downstream.

Make HttpConnection.connect return full working connections. <enter>  <enter> Previously the returned connections required the caller to <enter> do extra work: setting up tunnels (which could require auth) <enter> and performing an SSL handshake. With this change we make a <enter> complete working connection in HttpConnection.connect(). <enter>  <enter> This will make it easier to fix fallback when a single domain <enter> has multiple IP addresses and some of those addresses are not <enter> reachable. <enter>  <enter> This will also make it easier to do SPDY through HTTP proxies.

Fix a race condition in Connection.isExpired(). <enter>  <enter> This was causing some SPDY connections to be evicted early, <enter> and preventing connection reuse. <enter>  <enter> The spdyConnectionReuse test becomes flaky with the <enter> fix that makes MockWebServer use different sequenceNumbers <enter> for different requests on the same socket. With the fix <enter> the test is no longer flaky. The old test wasn't good enough <enter> to detect what it wanted to detect! <enter>  <enter> This race has existed in the code since we added more <enter> aggressive time-based expiration in January 2013. In my <enter> basic tests the race impacted ~20% of connections on a <enter> desktop VM. It may have been more on mobile.

Fix MavenSettings ?handling of profiles activated by a file <enter>  <enter> Previously, MavenSettings used a FileProfileActivator with no <enter> PathTransformer. If a settings.xml file contains a file-activated <enter> profile this would result in an NPE within Maven. This was made worse <enter> by the NPE not being included in the resulting failure message which <enter> hampered diagnosis of the problem. <enter>  <enter> This commit updates MavenSettings to configure its FileProfileActivator <enter> with a PathTransformer. It also improves the failure message that’s <enter> created from any problems that are reported by Maven while determining <enter> the active profiles to include a problem’s exception if it has one. <enter>  <enter> Closes gh-4826

OkBuffer API sketch. <enter>  <enter> I'm unhappy with java.io: <enter>  * No timeouts. <enter>  * Every layer needs to copy bytes around. Always copying bytes. <enter>  * Features like mark/reset and available() are clumsy. <enter>  * Its awkard in mixed text/binary protocols like HTTP because <enter>    character decoding is separate and takes over the stream. <enter>  <enter> Unfortunately java.nio isn't better, just different: <enter>  * It's complex. <enter>  * Buffers are fixed size. <enter>  * No built-in buffer pooling. <enter>  * Features like mark/reset/position are clumsy. <enter>  <enter> This is an obnoxious attempt at a 3rd I/O interface, mostly <enter> inspired by InputStream and OutputStream, but using growable <enter> buffers instead of byte arrays as the core data container.

Fail HTTP/2 connections if the pong is not received. (#3878) <enter>  <enter> This removes the Ping abstraction from our http2 package. This was written as <enter> if it were a public API, but never exposed to any callers but tests. Removing <enter> it makes it easier to lock down how pings are used. <enter>  <enter> This also removes the NullServer class, replacing it with a new SocketPolicy <enter> on MockWebServer. The new SocketPolicy, STALL_SOCKET_AT_START, allows us to <enter> do TLS and negotiate an HTTP/2 connection without actually building a proper <enter> Http2Connection and without responding to pings. <enter>  <enter> The behavior in HTTP/2 connections is modeled after our behavior in web sockets. <enter> We count outgoing pings, incoming pongs, and confirm that the pongs are keeping <enter> up. If later we make this policy more sophisticated we can track the changes <enter> in both places. <enter>  <enter> Closes: https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/3261

Better diagnotics when ESCF subclass breaks with custom management port <enter>  <enter> When a custom management.port is used, the child context is configured <enter> with an EmbeddedServletContainerFactory bean that has the same class <enter> as the parent context’s EmbeddedServletContainerFactory bean. This <enter> ensures that the child context uses the same type of embedded container <enter> as its parent when there are multiple embedded containers on the <enter> classpath. It also causes a failure when the custom <enter> EmbeddedServletContainerFactory subclass cannot be instantiated, for <enter> example because it’s an anonymous inner-class. <enter>  <enter> This commit improves the diagnostics so that we fail fast with an <enter> information exception message when we detect that the embedded servlet <enter> container factory bean’s class cannot be instantiated. <enter>  <enter> Closes gh-6193

Disable Log4J2's shutdown hook by default <enter>  <enter> Log4J2 enables its shutdown hook by default. When the JVM is exiting, <enter> this creates a race between logging that happens during the <enter> application context being closed and Log4J2 being shut down such that <enter> the logging is lost. <enter>  <enter> This commit updates SpringBootConfigurationFactory so that it <enter> produces a custom sub-class of DefaultConfiguration that disables the <enter> shutdown hook by default. In addition to solving the problem described <enter> above, this also aligns the Log4J2 logging system with the <enter> logging.register-shutdown-hook property which defaults to false. <enter>  <enter> Closes gh-11360

Partially revert connection timeout behavior <enter>  <enter> Related to issue #1790. <enter>  <enter> If there is a *connection* timeout the next route should <enter> be tried. Timeouts during a request/response should <enter> probably not be retried. <enter>  <enter> The timeout/interrupt behavior was changed in PR #1257 <enter> for issue #1146. This modified both connection and <enter> request/response behavior. The issue reported was actually <enter> about the use of Thread.interrupt(), not timeouts, but the <enter> behavior change modified both behavior for interrupt and <enter> timeout. <enter>  <enter> PR #1388 split the handling of exceptions so that separate <enter> code now handles connection errors from that which handles <enter> request/response errors. It faithfully kept the behavior <enter> from PR #1257. <enter>  <enter> The modification of the timeout behavior during *connection* <enter> caused problems on Android. Now that the two types of error <enter> handling are split it's possible to deal with them <enter> differently and return the connection behavior to trying <enter> the next route. This does not modify behavior during <enter> request/response.

Relicense JUnit from CPL to EPL <enter>  <enter> EPL is the successor version of the CPL this makes re-licensing <enter> possible without seeking the approval of all contributors. <enter>  <enter> CPL is actively hurting JUnit adaptation, it the following cases the <enter> deciding factor against JUnit was CPL. In both cases EPL would have <enter> been fine. <enter> * Netbeans can't ship JUnit [4] <enter> * OpenJDK uses TestNG instead of JUnit [5] <enter>  <enter> Mike Milinkovich from the Eclipse Foundation wrote [1] <enter>  <enter> > Back in 2009, the CPL was superseded by the EPL. This means that the <enter> > EPL is the successor version of the CPL. It also means that using the <enter> > CPL is the licensing equivalent of using deprecated code. <enter> > <enter> > Because the EPL is the successor version to the CPL, the 'new version <enter> > re-licensing' clause in Section 7 of the CPL applies. In other words, <enter> > you can re-license your project without seeking the approval of all <enter> > of your contributors. <enter> > The CPL and EPL basically differ by about one sentence, which you can <enter> > see here. The difference relates to the scope of patent licenses <enter> > terminated should someone sue another party for patent infringement. <enter> > This is the kind of stuff that lawyers love, but most developers <enter> > don't really care about. <enter>  <enter> On the migration from CPL to EPL Mike Milinkovich wrote [2] <enter>  <enter> > There was a two step process that was followed to make this happen. <enter> > First, following the terms of the CPL, IBM assigned the <enter> > responsibility to serve as the Agreement Steward of the CPL to the <enter> > Eclipse Foundation. Second, the Eclipse Foundation officially <enter> > recognized the EPL 1.0 as the new version of the CPL 1.0. In OSI <enter> > license terminology, the EPL now supersedes the CPL. <enter> > <enter> > A quick read of the two licenses will quickly show that they are very <enter> > very close. Other than their names and (previously) their Agreement <enter> > Stewards, the only substantive difference is the breadth of the <enter> > patent license termination in the event of a patent law suit. (See <enter> > the second paragraph of Section 7.) For more information on the <enter> > relationship between the CPL and the EPL see the EPL FAQ. <enter>  <enter> You can find more information about the difference at [3]. <enter>  <enter> The new `LICENSE.txt` is based on a plain text version of the EPL with <enter> formatted so that the diff is a clean as possible. <enter>  <enter> I'll submit another pull request for the gh-pages branch. <enter>  <enter>  [1] http://mmilinkov.wordpress.com/2013/02/13/jruby-moves-to-the-epl/ <enter>  [2] http://mmilinkov.wordpress.com/2009/04/16/one-small-step-towards-reducing-license-proliferation/ <enter>  [3] http://www.eclipse.org/legal/eplfaq.php#EPLDIFFER <enter>  [4] https://netbeans.org/community/releases/70/relnotes.html#deprecated <enter>  [5] http://openjdk.java.net/jtreg/build.html

Ensure exceptions from methodBlock() don't result in unrooted tests. <enter>  <enter> The introduction of the runLeaf() method in BlockJUnit4ClassRunner in <enter> JUnit 4.9 introduced a regression with regard to exception handling. <enter>  <enter> Specifically, the invocation of methodBlock() is no longer executed <enter> within a try-catch block as was the case in previous versions of JUnit. <enter>  <enter> Custom modifications to methodBlock() or the methods it invokes may in <enter> fact throw exceptions. In such cases, exceptions thrown from <enter> methodBlock() cause the current test execution to abort immediately. As <enter> a result, the failing test method is unrooted in test reports, and <enter> subsequent test methods are never invoked. Furthermore, RunListeners <enter> registered with JUnit are not notified. <enter>  <enter> This commit addresses this issue by wrapping the invocation of <enter> methodBlock() within a try-catch block. If an exception is not thrown, <enter> the resulting Statement is passed to runLeaf(). If an exception is <enter> thrown, it is wrapped in a Fail statement which is passed to runLeaf(). <enter>  <enter> Closes #1066 <enter> Closes #1082

Move TLS retries / fallback into Connection. <enter>  <enter> API changes: <enter> 1) Added: Address.getCertificatePinner() <enter> 2) Incompatible API change: Address constructor no longer <enter> includes ConnectionSpecs. Removed getConnectionSpecs(). <enter> 3) Added: ConnectionSpec.isCompatible(SSLSocket) <enter> 4) Added: TlsVersion.javaName() <enter>  <enter> Implicit / semantic / internal changes: <enter>  <enter> 1) Connection now handles all attempts to connect via a route <enter> (effectively a {proxy, socket address} pair), rather than just <enter> one attempt. i.e. Connection now handles all the TLS negotiation <enter> fallbacks internally. <enter>  <enter> 2) Route no longer deals with TLS versions. Individual TLS <enter> failures are not counted against a Route. If no connection <enter> attempts to a route were successful the failure is counted <enter> against the route. <enter>  <enter> 3) The code makes a distinction between when various <enter> IOExceptions occur, with the intention making retries a bit <enter> smarter. It is now more obvious which exceptions happen during <enter> setup (RequestException), connection (RouteException), <enter> HTTP communication and thus which can be retried and whether <enter> the request might have been sent.

Often the <enter> exception is thrown during a subsequent test. <enter>  <enter> This change logs the exception but prevent it from <enter> propagating out of the top of the call stack. Fix flaky DuplexTest.duplexWithRedirect <enter>  <enter> The test is flaky because the server sometimes acts on the 301 response and resets the stream before the action added by MockDuplexResponseBody.sendResponse() is executed. This action then fails because it tries to write to a reset stream. mockDuplexResponseBody.awaitSuccess() then throws and fails the test. <enter>  <enter> The change enforces the de-facto sequence on most runs, where the 301 response is handled only after the Duplex response is sent. <enter>  <enter> Fixes https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/4743

Return HttpResponseCache to previous (e.g. KitKat) behavior <enter>  <enter> This change required to handle this Android scenario: <enter>  <enter> When this version of OkHttp is packaged into Android in a future <enter> release (in com.android.okhttp...) there is a possibility that <enter> an older version of OkHttp bundled with application <enter> (in com.squareup.okhttp...) will pick up the newer HttpResponseCache <enter> via ResponseCache.getDefault(). It will attempt to use the get() / put() <enter> methods. Commit e2599be9e073f1be8e929597c358e2664ab0c9a9 was <enter> intended to restore HttpResponseCache get() and put() and avoid the <enter> UnsupportedOperationException that would be thrown. <enter>  <enter> Unfortunately, it didn't quite do it: <enter>  <enter> In KitKat and older versions OkHttp, in HttpResponseCache the behavior <enter> was to ignore any calls to put(URI, URLConnection) including <enter> any HttpURLConnection/HttpsURLConnection that wasn't its own <enter> (i.e. only ones from com.android.okhttp would be cached). The previous <enter> fix to HttpResponseCache re-introduced get()/put() but didn't implement <enter> the necessary instanceof checks. <enter>  <enter> Jesse also informs me that coexistance with other implementations <enter> of HttpURLConnection is not required (since OkHttp replaces the <enter> HTTP implementation on the desktop). I have also since discovered <enter> that HttpResponseCache didn't implement the cache-control logic <enter> required to follow the letter of the Java API anyway, which means <enter> that HttpResponseCache is not suitable for use in cases where <enter> the Http(s)URLConnection implementation expects a fully compliant <enter> implementation. <enter>  <enter> Also addressed nits from e2599be9e073f1be8e929597c358e2664ab0c9a9.

Allow HTAB in header values. <enter>  <enter> RFC 7230 section 3.2 allows HTAB ('	', 'u0009') inside header <enter> values as long as there is not more than one in a row: <enter>   https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7230#section-3.2 <enter>  <enter> Before this CL, OkHttp previously disallowed HTAB in header values. <enter> This CL changes behavior to allow any number of consecutive HTABs <enter> inside a header value; this is more permissive than the RFC, but <enter> is consistent with how OkHttp currently treats space characters <enter> (' ', 'u0020').

Bug: ParentRunner lost test Class from a separate class loader (#1252) <enter>  <enter> * Bug: ParentRunner lost test Class from a separate class loader <enter>  <enter> When junit.jar located in one ClassLoader but runing tests in another ParentRunner can lost information about run class. <enter> For example if use @ClassRule and request test class(org.junit.runner.Description#getTestClass) we can get null, <enter> because ParentRunner instead of set Class as is to Description tranform it to class name string, <enter> as result org.junit.runner.Description#getTestClass execute Class.forName and can't find test class. <enter>  <enter> Spring-test fail with exception if we try use SpringClassRule <enter>  <enter> ``` <enter> java.lang.NullPointerException <enter>  at org.springframework.test.context.junit4.rules.SpringClassRule.validateSpringMethodRuleConfiguration(SpringClassRule.java:186) <enter>  at org.springframework.test.context.junit4.rules.SpringClassRule.apply(SpringClassRule.java:134) <enter>  at org.junit.rules.RunRules.applyAll(RunRules.java:26) <enter>  at org.junit.rules.RunRules.<init>(RunRules.java:15) <enter>  at org.junit.runners.ParentRunner.withClassRules(ParentRunner.java:245) <enter>  at org.junit.runners.ParentRunner.classBlock(ParentRunner.java:194) <enter>  at org.junit.runners.ParentRunner.run(ParentRunner.java:362) <enter>  at org.junit.runner.JUnitCore.run(JUnitCore.java:137) <enter> ``` <enter>  <enter> As solution, now ParentRunner create Descriptor with explicit specify Class, name and uses annotations. <enter>  <enter> * Restore backward compatibility with sub class of ParentRunner that override getName method <enter> * Add ParentRunnerClassLoaderTest to AllClassesTests suite

Notably, this would prevent LaunchedURLClassLoader from <enter> loading classes or resources on an interrupted thread. <enter>  <enter> The previous commit (937f857) updates RandomAccessDataFile to acquire <enter> the semaphore uninterruptibly. This commit adds a test to <enter> LaunchedURLClassLoader to verify that it can now load a resource from <enter> an interrupted thread. <enter>  <enter> Closes gh-6683
